'''Jack Nicholas Pritzker''' (January 6, 1904 - October 30, 1979)<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/477277/Pritzker-family Britannica: "Pritzker family"] retrieved July 21, 2013</ref> was an [[United States|American]] businessman and member of the [[Pritzker family]].

==Early life and education==
Jack Pritzker was the son of [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] [[Jewish]] immigrants Annie P. (n<U+00E9>e Cohn) and Nicholas J. Pritzker.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE5DB1439F936A15752C0A96F958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | title=Jay Pritzker, Who Built Chain Of Hyatt Hotels, Is Dead at 76 | first=Anthony | last=Ramirez | date=January 25, 1999 | accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://books.google.ca/books?id=RowMAQAAMAAJ&q=Annie+Cohn+Pritzker&dq=Annie+Cohn+Pritzker&hl=en]</ref> His father left Kiev for Chicago in 1881 and worked first as a pharmacist and then a lawyer.<ref name=CNNMoney>[http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1988/04/25/70462/index.htm CNN Money: "THE PRITZKERS UNVEILING A PRIVATE FAMILY" By Ford S. Worthy] April 25, 1988</ref> He graduated from [[Northwestern Law School]] in 1927.<ref> Silbiger, Steve [http://books.google.com/books?id=Qp-kDuWkiAoC&pg=PA33&lpg=PA33&dq=jack+nicholas+pritzker&source=bl&ots=zLPVIlCa_4&sig=_qctMGjGtI_WGyc9m2OYwSufMKM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=E4HsUdmZJvjl4AO1goDYBA&ved=0CEMQ6AEwBDge#v=onepage&q=jack%20nicholas%20pritzker&f=false ''The Jewish Phenomenon: Seven Keys to the Enduring Wealth of a People'']</ref> His father wrote a small book that has been passed down from Pritzker to Pritzker; the theme of the book is "Your only immortality is the impact you have on your successors."<ref name=CNNMoney />

==Career==
Harry joined his father's law firm, ''Pritzker & Pritzker'', along with his brothers, [[Abram Nicholas Pritzker|Abram]] and [[Harry Nicholas Pritzker|Harry]].<ref name=CNNMoney /> Harry specialized in criminal law, Abram (called Abe and later A. N.) specialized in business law, and Jack in real estate law.<ref name=NYTDealAndMultiply>[http://www.nytimes.com/1984/02/26/business/how-they-deal-and-multiply.html New York Times: "HOW THEY DEAL AND MULTIPLY" By Marylin Bender] February 26, 1984</ref> In the 1930s, he left the law practice and branched out with his brother Jack investing in real estate and small companies mostly in the [[Chicago]] area.<ref name=CNNMoney /> Harry continued to run the law firm which eventually became an in-house firm catering solely to the needs of the Pritzker family and its business.<ref name=CNNMoney /> The Pritzker brothers were very successful and amassed a considerable fortune. Using ''Pritzker & Pritzker'', they shielded their earnings from taxes through a series of trusts and tax code loopholes enabling them to distribute their earnings as they chose.<ref>[http://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/December-2002/Tremors-in-the-Empire/ Chicago magazine: "Tremors in the Empire" by By Shane Tritsch] December 2002</ref> 

His brother Abram's sons continued to grow the family business eventually buying the [[Hyatt Hotel|Hyatt]] House hotel in [[Los Angeles]] in 1957 forming the cornerstone of their hotel chain. His nephew Robert created a conglomerate of a multitude of manufacturing companies which grew into the multi billion dollar [[Marmon Group]]. Marmon was diversified to include manufacturing concerns ranging from lumber to railroad box cars and travel industry staples.  It composed half of the family's wealth. On December 25, 2007, it was announced that Warren Buffett, through [[Berkshire Hathaway]], would purchase 60% of the Marmon Group from the Pritzkers for $4.5 Billion.<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/26/business/26deal.html New York Times: "Rapidly, Buffett Secures a Deal for $4.5 Billion" By VIKAS BAJAJ] December 26, 2007</ref>

==Personal life==
Pritzker was married to [[Rhoda Pritzker|Rhoda Goldberg]]; they had one child: [[Nicholas J. Pritzker]] who is chairman of the board and CEO of the Hyatt Development Corporation.<ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/19990206/ISSUE01/10001555?template=printart Crain's Chicago Business: "TORCH GETS PASSED AT PRITZKERS' MEGA-EMPIRE" by Paul Merrion] February 06, 1999</ref>

